{"cursor":"10508","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn actuarial science and demography, a 'life table' (also called a 'mortality\ntable' or 'actuarial table') is a table which shows, for each age, what the\nprobability is that a person of that age will die before his or her next\nbirthday (\"probability of death\"). From this starting point, a number of\ninferences can be derived.\n\n*the probability of surviving any particular year of age *remaining life\nexpectancy for people at different ages\n\nLife tables are also used extensively in biology and epidemiology. The concept\nis also of importance in product life cycle management.\n","linknr":191,"url":"Actuarial_table","recorded":1362484702,"links":26,"instances":["statistics"],"pdf":["http://www.soa.org/library/monographs/retirement-systems/living-to-100-and-beyond/2005/january/m-li05-1-ix.pdf","http://www.soa.org/library/monographs/retirement-systems/living-to-100-and-beyond/2005/january/m-li05-1-ix.pdf"],"categories":["Actuarial science","Demography","Population","Statistical data types","Insurance"],"headings":["Background","Insurance applications","The mathematics","Ending a Mortality Table","Epidemiology","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Excerpt_from_CDC_2003_Table_1.pdf/page1-220px-Excerpt_from_CDC_2003_Table_1.pdf.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/5b/Data_from_National_Vital_Statistics_Report_tPx.png/220px-Data_from_National_Vital_Statistics_Report_tPx.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/8/3/883465c02a6ef0dc2dfa5472a615310e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/9/b/c9b156d8b2ef3e299acca75219990b56.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/4/a/f4ab253695b2094ece6d0b738855650c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/8/e/d8ee35fa29e6864120c85399a56c4d05.png